# Phase 7a: Supabase Auth env plumbing. Copy this file to `.env.local`
# (never committed -- see .gitignore) and UNCOMMENT + fill in both values
# below from `supabase status` (after `supabase start`) to opt INTO auth
# mode. Left as-is (both lines commented out), a verbatim `cp .env.example
# .env.local` yields real demo mode -- verified: `next build`/`next dev`
# with the file copied byte-for-byte start clean, no 500s. This matters
# because BOTH variables must be set together or neither: `isSupabaseConfigured()`
# (lib/supabase/config.ts) and middleware.ts both fail closed (redirect to
# `/login` rather than crash) if only the URL is set without the key --
# but there is no in-app recovery from a half-configured pair either way,
# so this file ships with NEITHER uncommented, never one pre-filled and the
# other blank (that half-configured shape previously 500'd on every route,
# `/login` included, with no way to self-recover short of editing the file).
#
# ABSENCE of NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL = localStorage demo mode: no auth
# redirect (middleware.ts is a pass-through), no sidebar session footer,
# Phase 1-6 flows unchanged. This is the repo's default state -- Phase 7
# route handlers / HttpReportsRepository (Phase 7b) are opt-in via these
# two variables, not required to run the app.

# The local Supabase API URL (from `supabase status` -- "API URL" / "REST").
# NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:54321

# The anon/public key (from `supabase status` -- "anon key" / "Publishable").
# Safe to expose client-side: RLS (supabase/migrations/*.sql) is what
# actually enforces access, not secrecy of this key.
# NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=

# That's all Phase 7 needs -- route handlers act as the cookie-bound user
# and RLS enforces from there.

# Phase 8a: the remote MCP server (/api/mcp) needs ONE more secret, this
# project's legacy Supabase JWT secret -- server-only, deliberately NOT
# prefixed NEXT_PUBLIC_ (never shipped to the client bundle). It's what
# lib/server/mcp-auth.ts uses to hand-sign a short-lived (5 minute) HS256
# JWT for a verified MCP bearer token, so `reports-service.ts` can run
# under that user's own RLS -- see that file's header comment for the full
# auth bridge. Locally: `supabase status`'s "JWT secret" value (the CLI's
# well-known local default is
# "super-secret-jwt-token-with-at-least-32-characters-long" unless your
# `supabase/config.toml` overrides it). In production: the Supabase
# dashboard's Settings -> API -> "JWT Secret" (the LEGACY one, not an
# asymmetric signing key -- see mcp-auth.ts's "documented caveat" for what
# happens if that legacy secret is ever fully revoked).
#
# Absence of this value (with Supabase otherwise configured) means
# `/api/mcp` 404s on every call -- but Settings' "Claude (MCP) Access"
# section is still SHOWN (it's gated on Supabase being configured, not on
# this secret): it displays a "not configured yet" notice and still lets an
# operator create tokens (a token created now works retroactively once this
# value is set -- nothing needs to be re-minted). See
# lib/server/mcp-auth.ts's `isMcpConfigured()` and
# components/settings/McpAccessSection.tsx's `endpointReady` handling.
# Everything else in Supabase mode is unaffected.
# SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET=

# The service-role key STILL stays out of this file -- Phase 8's MCP server
# never needed it either (see lib/server/mcp-auth.ts's header comment: every
# MCP call runs as the `authenticated` role via a per-request, user-scoped
# JWT, exactly like the web cookie path, never as service-role). If a future
# phase genuinely needs one, treat adding it here as a security review on
# its own, not a routine env addition.
